===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|deaþ|dēaþ}}, from {{proto|Germanic|dauþuz}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|dʰautus}}.  Cognate with West Frisian {{term|dead|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|dood}}, German {{term|Tod}}, Swedish {{term|död}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|dĕth}}, {{IPA|/dɛθ/}}, {{SAMPA|/dET/}}
* {{audio|en-us-death.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*: {{rhymes|ɛθ}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The [[cessation]] of [[life]] and all associated processes; the [[end]] of an [[organism]]'s [[existence]] as an [[entity]] independent from its environment and its return to an [[inert]], [[nonliving]] state.
#: ''The '''death''' of my grandmother saddened the whole family.''
# {{often|capitalized}} The [[personification]] of death as a [[hooded]] figure with a [[scythe]]; the [[Grim Reaper]].
#: ''When '''death''' walked in, a chill spread through the room.''

